[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    715[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m        document_id="doc-2026-05-01-discharge-00482",[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    716[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m        clinical_text=sample_clinical_text,[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    717[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m    )[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    718[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    719[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m    # Pretty-print the result. DynamoDB Decimal objects aren't JSON-serializable[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    720[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m    # by default, so we convert them to float for display.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    721[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m    class DecimalEncoder(json.JSONEncoder):[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    722[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m        def default(self, obj):[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    723[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m            if isinstance(obj, Decimal):[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    724[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m                return float(obj)[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    725[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m            return super().default(obj)[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    726[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    727[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m    print(json.dumps(result, indent=2, cls=DecimalEncoder))[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    728[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m```[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    729[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    730[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m---[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    731[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    732[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;143;161;179m##[38;2;192;197;206m [38;2;143;161;179mThe Gap Between This and Production[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    733[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    734[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206mThis example works. Point it at a real Bedrock endpoint and Comprehend Medical, feed it clinical text, and it will produce a simplified version with readability scores and entity validation. But the distance between "works as a script" and "runs at a health system simplifying thousands of documents per day" is significant. Here's where that gap lives.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    735[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    736[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mError handling.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Every external call here can fail. Bedrock can throttle under load. Comprehend Medical has a 20,000 character limit per request (longer documents need chunking). DynamoDB can reject items over 400KB. A production system wraps each call in try/except with specific handling for [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mThrottlingException[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m, [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mValidationException[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m, and [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mServiceUnavailableException[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m. Failed documents go to a dead-letter queue, not into the void.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    737[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    738[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mComprehend Medical character limits.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m The [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mdetect_entities_v2[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m API accepts a maximum of 20,000 UTF-8 characters per request. Most discharge summaries and lab results fit within this, but long hospital course summaries or multi-page documents will exceed it. A production system chunks text at sentence boundaries, processes each chunk separately, and merges the entity lists. Splitting mid-sentence can cause entity detection failures at chunk boundaries.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    739[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    740[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mEntity matching sophistication.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m The [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mvalidate_accuracy[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m function uses simple substring matching to compare entities. This works for exact matches ("aspirin" in both texts) but misses semantic equivalents. The original might say "myocardial infarction" while the simplified version says "heart attack." Both refer to the same condition, but substring matching won't connect them. A production system needs a medical synonym map or a secondary LLM call to verify semantic equivalence.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    741[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    742[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mReadability scoring limitations.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m The [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mtextstat[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m library measures surface complexity (syllable count, sentence length) but not conceptual complexity. A sentence using only short words can still be confusing if the concept is abstract. "Your blood does not clot well" scores as grade 4 but might confuse a patient who doesn't know what clotting means. Use readability scores as a floor, not a ceiling. Supplement with periodic human evaluation.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    743[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    744[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mPrompt versioning.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m This example uses a hardcoded prompt. A production system stores prompts in S3 (versioned bucket), routes a percentage of traffic to new prompt versions for A/B testing, and tracks readability scores and validation pass rates per prompt version. When a new prompt improves scores, promote it. When it degrades, roll back.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    745[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    746[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mBatch processing.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m This example processes one document at a time. A health system generating hundreds of discharge summaries per day needs batch processing: an SQS queue feeding Lambda invocations, with concurrency limits to avoid Bedrock throttling. Consider Bedrock batch inference for high-volume, non-real-time workloads.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    747[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    748[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mCaching.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Many clinical documents contain repeated phrases and standard language. "Follow up in 2 weeks" appears in thousands of discharge summaries. A production system can cache simplifications of common phrases to reduce Bedrock calls and improve latency. Use a TTL-based cache (ElastiCache or DynamoDB) keyed on a hash of the input text.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    749[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    750[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mMulti-language support.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m This example produces English simplified text only. For patient populations with limited English proficiency, you'd add a translation step after simplification. Simplify first (in English), then translate. Translating complex clinical English directly produces worse results than translating already-simplified English. Amazon Translate handles the translation step.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    751[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    752[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mVPC and network isolation.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m In production, this Lambda runs in a VPC with private subnets. VPC endpoints for Bedrock, Comprehend Medical, DynamoDB, and CloudWatch keep all traffic on the AWS backbone. Clinical text is PHI. It should never traverse the public internet.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    753[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    754[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mEncryption.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m This example relies on default encryption. Production uses KMS customer-managed keys for the DynamoDB table and CloudWatch Logs. Enable key rotation. Log every key usage via CloudTrail.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    755[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    756[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mStructured logging and metrics.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m The [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mlogger.info()[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m calls here are a start. Production needs structured JSON logs with consistent fields: document_id, doc_type, model_id, attempt_count, latency_ms, readability_grade, validation_passed. Emit CloudWatch metrics for: simplification latency (p50, p95), readability score distribution, validation pass rate, retry rate, and human review rate. The validation pass rate is your north star metric.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    757[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    758[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mHuman review workflow.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m Documents that fail accuracy validation route to "human review," but this example doesn't implement the review queue. In production, failed documents go to an SQS queue that feeds a review UI where health literacy specialists can edit the simplified text, approve it, or flag the original as too complex for automated simplification.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    759[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    760[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;235;203;139mTesting.[38;2;235;203;139m**[38;2;192;197;206m There are no tests here. A production pipeline has: unit tests for [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mclassify_document[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m with edge cases, integration tests against Bedrock with known clinical text samples, validation tests confirming that intentionally degraded simplifications (dropped medications, changed doses) are caught by [38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;163;190;140mvalidate_accuracy[38;2;163;190;140m`[38;2;192;197;206m, and readability regression tests ensuring prompt changes don't degrade grade level scores. Never use real patient documents in test fixtures. Use synthetic clinical text.[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    761[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    762[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;192;197;206m---[K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    763[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [K
[0m[48;2;40;67;43m[39m+    764[0m:[39m[48;2;24;38;30m [38;2;180;142;173m*[38;2;180;142;173mPart of the Healthcare AI/ML Cookbook. See [38;2;208;135;112m[[38;2;208;135;112mRecipe 2.2: Medical Terminology Simplification[38;2;208;135;112m][38;2;208;135;112m([38;2;208;135;112mchapter02.02-medical-terminology-simplification[38;2;208;135;112m)[38;2;180;142;173m for the full architectural walkthrough, pseudocode, and honest take on where this gets hard.[38;2;180;142;173m*[K
